unicating ideas, regarded as egocentric, not willing to further education, keeps calm in a crisis, understands complicated technology. Candidate D responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously, regarded as a know-it-all, has a hot temper.\n\nWe need to evaluate for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calmness under pressure, decision-making, teamwork, professional development.\n\nLet's weigh each:\n\nA: strong anticipation, complex connections, spatial vision, leadership. Weakness: show-off, not open to new ideas. No explicit calmness. Leadership good but maybe overconfidence. No teamwork info.\n\nB: conscientious, handles stress well (calmness), good weather assessment (technical), excellent computer skills (tech), but weak memory for numbers (could be issue), makes nasty remarks (teamwork/crew cooperation negative). Conscientiousness good reliability. Stress handling is a plus.\n\nC: quick correct decisions, keeps calm in crisis (calmness), understands complicated tech, but difficulty communicating, egocentric, not willing to further education (professional development), concern for others above everything (maybe teamwork). Mixed.\n\nD: responds to unexpected events adequately, concentrates, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously (reliability), but hot temper (calmness issue), know-it-all (teamwork). No explicit calmness.\n\nThus best overall may be B or C. B has stress handling, conscientiousness, but poor teamwork (nasty remarks) and weak memory for numbers. C has calmness, quick decisions, technical, but poor communication, egocentric, not willing to develop. For long-distance flights, crew cooperation is critical; nasty remarks could be dangerous. C's egocentric and communication difficulty also problematic. B's stress handling is good, but nasty remarks could undermine crew. Which is more severe? Probably teamwork issues are critical. C also has communication difficulty, but also shows concern for others. B's nasty remarks are explicit negative behavior. I'd lean towards Candidate C perhaps, but need to consider that C's egocentric and unwillingness to further education may affect long-term suitability. However, calmness and quick correct decisions are vital. B's technical competence (weather, computer) is good, but memory for numbers could be mitigated? Not sure.\n\nWe need to state provisional preference, with uncertainty. I think we can say Undecided, but we need to give a preference. The instruction: \"State your current preferred candidate; ... If you cannot yet choose, vote Undecided.\" We have enough info to make a provisional preference. I think Candidate C seems strongest in calmness and decision-making, but teamwork concerns. Candidate B has stress handling but poor teamwork. Both have issues. I might be leaning toward Candidate C because calmness under pressure and quick correct decisions are crucial for long-distance flights, and concern for others may offset some teamwork deficits. So provisional preference: Candidate C, with moderate confidence, pending more info on teamwork and willingness to develop.\n\nWe should note uncertainties: communication, egocentric, lack of willingness to further education. Also need more info on B's teamwork behavior specifics, D's calmness, A's calmness.\n\nThus produce public message."}
